§a The sact that dolus was not essential to constitute damnum iniuria datum distinguishes it clearly from the three other delicts: ‘when culpa is once established, the amount oi the defendant’s liability does not depend on its degree ;' ‘in lege Aquilia et levissima culpa venit' Dig. q 2. 44. pr, ‘culpam autem esse, quod, cum a diligente pro- videri potuerit, non esse provisum' ib. 31: cf. §rint The idea is sul- ficiently illustrated in the next five sections.

lt is a much argued question whether very slight negligence in a party to a legal relation in which he was answerable for culpa lata only would entitle the other party to sue him under the lex Aquilia; as where a depositary by slight negligence causes destruction oi or damage to the res deposita The true answer depends on the correct appreciation of a rather fine distinction. Some acts are acquitted os culpa, is there be alegal relation between the parties, which would otherwise be imputable ; e. g. a delicate piece of glass work is given to an artificer to repair, and breaks to pieces in his hands through no want of skill or cantion on his part. But ir the act is one which is not excused by virtue os the legal relation, the actio legis Aquiliae will lie, because the delinquent is ex· empted from liability ior culpa levis only in respect ol the specific duties which that relation imposes on him, Dig. 4o 12. 13. pr.; 47.41.2; 925&
